                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14461338" author="mdaniel" created="Wed, 10 Aug 2005 14:11:23 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This is present in 1.0-jsr-03, too&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I am extremely rusty on Antlr syntax. What does the following grammar snippet do, with especial emphasis on the statement&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;COLON&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; part?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;caseSList  &lt;/p&gt;
{Token first = LT(1);}
&lt;p&gt;    :   statement&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;COLON&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; (sep! (statement&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;sepToken&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt;)?)*&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14461572" author="wangbin" created="Mon, 12 Sep 2005 22:01:16 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The java.g  is &lt;br/&gt;
casesGroup&lt;br/&gt;
    :   (   // CONFLICT: to which case group do the statements bind?&lt;br/&gt;
            //           ANTLR generates proper code: it groups the&lt;br/&gt;
            //           many &quot;case&quot;/&quot;default&quot; labels together then&lt;br/&gt;
            //           follows them with the statements&lt;br/&gt;
            options &lt;/p&gt;
{
                greedy = true;
            }&lt;br/&gt;
            :&lt;br/&gt;
            aCase&lt;br/&gt;
        )+&lt;br/&gt;
        caseSList&lt;br/&gt;
        {#casesGroup = #([CASE_GROUP, &quot;CASE_GROUP&quot;], #casesGroup);}&lt;br/&gt;
    ;&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
aCase&lt;br/&gt;
    :   (&quot;case&quot;^ expression | &quot;default&quot;) COLON!&lt;br/&gt;
    ;&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
caseSList&lt;br/&gt;
    :   (statement)*&lt;br/&gt;
        {#caseSList = #(#[SLIST,&quot;SLIST&quot;],#caseSList);}&lt;br/&gt;
    ;&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
in groovy.g file:&lt;br/&gt;
// Support for switch/case:&lt;br/&gt;
casesGroup  {Token first = LT(1);}&lt;br/&gt;
    :   (   // CONFLICT: to which case group do the statements bind?&lt;br/&gt;
            // ANTLR generates proper code: it groups the&lt;br/&gt;
            // many &quot;case&quot;/&quot;default&quot; labels together then&lt;br/&gt;
            // follows them with the statements&lt;br/&gt;
            options {                greedy = true;            }
&lt;p&gt;            :&lt;br/&gt;
            aCase&lt;br/&gt;
        )+&lt;br/&gt;
        caseSList&lt;/p&gt;
        {#casesGroup = #(create(CASE_GROUP, &quot;CASE_GROUP&quot;,first,LT(1)), #casesGroup);}
&lt;p&gt;    ;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;aCase&lt;br/&gt;
    :   (&quot;case&quot;^ expression&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;0&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; | &quot;default&quot;) COLON! nls!&lt;br/&gt;
    ;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;caseSList  &lt;/p&gt;
{Token first = LT(1);}
&lt;p&gt;    :   statement&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;COLON&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; (sep! (statement&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;sepToken&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt;)?)*&lt;/p&gt;
        {#caseSList = #(create(SLIST,&quot;SLIST&quot;,first,LT(1)),#caseSList);}
&lt;p&gt;    ;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14461858" author="guillaume" created="Sun, 9 Apr 2006 10:35:22 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The problem is still present in CVS Head. Can we do something about it?&lt;br/&gt;
At least, there&apos;s the workaround of using ranges, or lists to group certain cases in the same case, but I think this should be fixed anyway.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14462395" author="russel" created="Sat, 28 Oct 2006 01:10:33 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Still can&apos;t have case statement fall-through in Subversion r1479.  &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GROOVY-1310&quot; title=&quot;Switch cases not working&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;GROOVY-1310&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;GROOVY-1310&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GROOVY-1447&quot; title=&quot;Cannot have fallthrough of case labels&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;GROOVY-1447&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;GROOVY-1447&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; replicate this issue.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yes, there are work-arounds but fall-through causing a compilation error does violate the Principle of Least Surprise.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We should probably raise the priority of this issue?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14462210" author="tof" created="Sat, 28 Oct 2006 12:36:01 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Since the case statement now is based on the isCase method I prefer to use:&lt;br/&gt;
switch(1) {&lt;br/&gt;
  case &lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;1, 2&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt;:&lt;br/&gt;
    println &quot;1 or 2&quot;&lt;br/&gt;
    break&lt;br/&gt;
}&lt;br/&gt;
In fact I would discourage the use of the stacked case.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14462374" author="russel" created="Mon, 30 Oct 2006 01:27:12 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Well an alternative is to enforce this as Groovy and declare fall-through to be a compile error.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The only problem with that is:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;case X :&lt;br/&gt;
   &amp;lt;some code&amp;gt;&lt;br/&gt;
   // Fall-through&lt;br/&gt;
case Y :&lt;br/&gt;
   &amp;lt;more code&amp;gt;&lt;br/&gt;
   break&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I agree there are way around this as well but they are generally very messy in those few situation where fall-through like this is useful.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14477228" author="paulk" created="Tue, 5 Dec 2006 21:34:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;should be fixed in HEAD&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14462464" author="russel" created="Wed, 6 Dec 2006 05:15:37 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Seems to be fixed as claimed so closing.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
